<h2 id="chord-progression">Chord progression</h2>

<p>Repeat this for the entire song. Intro, verse, and chorus â€“ they all use this basic progression. Remember, 4 counts per measure.</p>

<div class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>G . . . D . . . Am . . . Am . . .
G . . . D . . . C  . . . C  . . .
</code></pre></div></div>

<h2 id="strumming-pattern">Strumming pattern</h2>

<p>The ideal strumming pattern you should strive to play is:</p>

<div class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>1 + 2 + 3 + 4 +
D       D   D U
</code></pre></div></div>

<p>If youâ€™re having trouble with this, start simple. Begin with a single downstrum on the â€œ1â€ count of each 4-count measure:</p>

<div class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>1 + 2 + 3 + 4 +
D       
</code></pre></div></div>

<p>When you can do that, add another down strum to the 3 count:</p>

<div class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>1   2   3   4  
D       D
</code></pre></div></div>

<p>After that, add yet another down strum on the 4 count:</p>

<div class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>1 + 2 + 3 + 4 +
D       D   D
</code></pre></div></div>

<p>And finally, when you can do whatâ€™s above reliably well enough, add a single upstrum on the â€œ4 andâ€ count:</p>

<div class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>1 + 2 + 3 + 4 +
D       D   D U
</code></pre></div></div>

<p>Repeat this pattern for the entire song. Though of course, should you wish, you could get creative and use any strumming pattern you like.</p>

